[{"sha":"0afd6b2dab175bfec5e3644243b8a24dd6ca4aaa","author":{"name":"Lei Zhang","email":"e75249ddeeeca9f9b303259f003613466bb8da5c@google.com"},"message":"Use the correct shape when converting mhlo.reshape

If mhlo.reshape is not purely collapsing some consecutive operand
dimensions into result dimensions, we will generate two linalg
reshape op for it: the first one collapses all operand dimensions
into one dimension, and the second one expands it to all result
dimensions. For this case, the number of collapsed/expanded dimensions
should be coming strictly from the operand/result. It is different
from the case where we can generate one linalg reshape. For that case,
the reassociation map should have rank equal to the largest among
operand/result shape.

[{"sha":"6464b28dade036a5fa64df3dbe4e14d289fb94bd","author":{"name":"Shlomi Regev","email":"6656f50999d95a610b9c4c463eddb5f0e5ffbfd4@google.com"},"message":"Allocate input and output tensors from persistent memory during micro interpreter initialization.

Until now, only input and output tensors index 0 were allocated and cached and only when first accessed (not on init). For index > 0, a new tensor was created for every call to MicroInterpreter::input() or MicroInterpreter::output(). For models with more than one input or output, this amounts to a memory leak.

Also change //third_party/tensorflow/lite/micro:memory_arena_threshold_test arena size threshold to account for the new allocation. Until now, the test never allocated input and output tensor because it doesn't call MicroInterpreter::input() or MicroInterpreter::output().

[{"sha":"e3e806ea76c4716f092125fdec8580c7da1bf9f2","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"[XLA] Fix implementation of igamma and igammac for f16 and bf16.

The implementation was supposed to work for f16 and bf16 by upcasting
to f32. The problem was that when computing constants list `Epsilon` and
`MaxFiniteValue` for the precision of the original type (e.g., `f16`) they
are used in computation along with upcast operands, leading to error:

```
Seen floating point types of different precisions in %compare.198 = pred[1,1,3]{2,1,0} compare(f32[1,1,3]{2,1,0} %divide.195, f16[1,1,3]{2,1,0} %broadcast.197), direction=GT, but mixed precision is disallowed.
```

The fix is to use Epsilon for the new type of the computation (F32). This produces values that are more accurate w.r.t. scipy than trying to use Epsilon at F16 and then upcasting it to the type of the surrounding computation.

[{"sha":"8bc0c84e45f1e172bfa81e9cc5fd4302a7d362e9","author":{"name":"Skye Wanderman-Milne","email":"4c878c1ae364587078acae22009e8542fed717b6@google.com"},"message":"[libtpu] Make copies of data returned by getenv.

According to http://www.cplusplus.com/reference/cstdlib/getenv/:
The pointer returned points to an internal memory block, whose content
or validity may be altered by further calls to getenv (but not by
other library functions).

This appears to have been working without the defensive copies, but we
should follow the spec just in case.

This change also refactors TfTpu_Initialize to not use the argc/argv
convention for simplicity (the implementation doesn't actually require
a nullptr at the end of argv).

[{"sha":"1342c51d5e809d2994e6f7e490c8d2b3b12c28ae","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Ensure MkdirAllAndChown also sets perms

Generally if we ever need to change perms of a dir, between versions,
this ensures the permissions actually change when we think it should
change without having to handle special cases if it already existed.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>
(cherry picked from commit edb62a3ace8c4303822a391b38231e577f8c2ee8)
Signed-off-by: Tibor Vass <tibor@docker.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/moby/moby/commits/1342c51d5e809d2994e6f7e490c8d2b3b12c28ae"},{"sha":"5eff67a2c294b7e72607e0949ebc0de21710e4d3","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Do not set DOCKER_TMP to be owned by remapped root

The remapped root does not need access to this dir.
Having this owned by the remapped root opens the host up to an
uprivileged user on the host being able to escalate privileges.

While it would not be normal for the remapped UID to be used outside of
the container context, it could happen.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>
(cherry picked from commit bfedd2725971303efb7a2fe5d6990317b381622f)
Signed-off-by: Tibor Vass <tibor@docker.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/moby/moby/commits/5eff67a2c294b7e72607e0949ebc0de21710e4d3"},{"sha":"67de83e70bca92ae6a08e28a03b3fc8fcca9f3f1","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Use real root with 0701 perms

Various dirs in /var/lib/docker contain data that needs to be mounted
into a container. For this reason, these dirs are set to be owned by the
remapped root user, otherwise there can be permissions issues.
However, this uneccessarily exposes these dirs to an unprivileged user
on the host.

Instead, set the ownership of these dirs to the real root (or rather the
UID/GID of dockerd) with 0701 permissions, which allows the remapped
root to enter the directories but not read/write to them.
The remapped root needs to enter these dirs so the container's rootfs
can be configured... e.g. to mount /etc/resolve.conf.

This prevents an unprivileged user from having read/write access to
these dirs on the host.
The flip side of this is now any user can enter these directories.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>

We have special handling for distributed variable in get_slot, but not
create_slot, while these keys need to match. This change modifies get_slot to use _var_key as well to avoid confusion. It is also to prepare for a upcoming refactor in dist strat code.

Note that we need to make sure the keys don't change, so existing checkpoints can still be used.

A bunch of build rules are modified to break cyclic dependencies.

[{"sha":"27801b9ef807ce64b55b4c4ccd9a02248ae6bce2","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"vendor: update github.com/Microsoft/hcsshim v0.8.10 (back to tagged release)

This switches the hcsshim dependency back to tagged releases, instead of the special
"moby" branch. This makes the dependency align with both BuildKit and containerd,
which use these versions.

The switch to the "moby" branch was done in 286547848751229fa14974da389e1d4c676d8ee5,
to bring in a fix for image import, without having to bring in additional changes;

> We changed to the moby branch for a couple of reasons:
>
> - Allows us to take this important change without needing to also pull in all
>   of the other work that has been going on in the repo.
> - moby uses an older set of APIs exposed from hcsshim, based on the HCS v1
>   functionality. Going forwards, we have discussed deprecating/removing these
>   APIs from the mainline branch in hcsshim, so our thinking was we could keep
>   this moby branch around to ensure we don't break compatibility there.
>
> (...) Long term, the best path here is to get moby using containerd as the
> backend on Windows, which should alleviate these issues.

full diff: https://github.com/Microsoft/hcsshim/compare/9dcb42f100215f8d375b4a9265e5bba009217a85..v0.8.10
